**Deployment-spec-level API defaults not normalized — infinite update loop in production**

`normalize.PodSpecDefaults` correctly handles pod-level defaults, but `apiequality.Semantic.DeepEqual(existing.Spec, *desiredSpec)` compares the full `DeploymentSpec`, which includes several fields that the API server defaults on first creation:

| Field | API-server default |
|---|---|
| `ProgressDeadlineSeconds` | `&600` |
| `RevisionHistoryLimit` | `&10` |
| `Strategy.Type` | `"RollingUpdate"` |
| `Strategy.RollingUpdate.MaxSurge` | `intstr.FromString("25%")` |
| `Strategy.RollingUpdate.MaxUnavailable` | `intstr.FromString("25%")` |

When a caller constructs a `Deployment` without setting these fields (the common case), `desiredSpec` retains `nil`/empty values while `existing.Spec` holds the API-server defaults. Because `apiequality.Semantic` falls back to `reflect.DeepEqual` for `*int32` and string fields, `nil != &600`, so the comparison returns `false` on every reconcile — triggering a spurious `c.Update` and increment of `Generation` indefinitely.

The fix is to extend `normalize.PodSpecDefaults` (or add a separate `normalize.DeploymentSpecDefaults`) to also fill in these fields:

```go
// In normalize/podspec.go (or a new deployment.go):
func DeploymentSpecDefaults(spec *appsv1.DeploymentSpec) {
    if spec.RevisionHistoryLimit == nil {
        v := int32(10)
        spec.RevisionHistoryLimit = &v
    }
    if spec.ProgressDeadlineSeconds == nil {
        v := int32(600)
        spec.ProgressDeadlineSeconds = &v
    }
    if spec.Strategy.Type == "" {
        spec.Strategy.Type = appsv1.RollingUpdateDeploymentStrategyType
    }
    if spec.Strategy.RollingUpdate == nil {
        twentyFive := intstr.FromString("25%")
        spec.Strategy.RollingUpdate = &appsv1.RollingUpdateDeployment{
            MaxSurge:       &twentyFive,
            MaxUnavailable: &twentyFive,
        }
    }
    PodSpecDefaults(&spec.Template.Spec)
}
```

Note: the fake client used in unit tests does not apply API-server defaults, so existing tests pass despite the bug — this will only surface in production or envtest integration tests.

